ke the world more optimistic and made the case for optimism in three parts:=
=20
We=E2=80=99re more pessimistic than we should be.
Optimism shapes reality.
The downside to optimism is limited, the upside is uncapped.
Part of the reason for the pessimism was that the press serves up the most =
negative stories it can find, and takes the most negative angle on even the=
 most positive stories. The view from my day job(s) =E2=80=94 writing this =
newsletter and investing at Not Boring Capital =E2=80=94 was completely dif=
ferent. Every day, I meet people doing things that seem straight out of the=
 pages of utopian sci-fi [ https://substack.com/redirect/24f34fde-4874-4d51=
-bd3f-c607848aa7d5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ]. Entrepreneurs, scientists, researchers, and all sorts of peop=
le are producing clean, abundant energy, curing cancer, giving hearing back=
 to deaf kids, launching huge rockets into space, landing them back on eart=
h, and building machines that can think. They=E2=80=99re fighting =E2=80=94=
 and often winning =E2=80=94 to make the world a better place.=20
But you wouldn=E2=80=99t know it if you opened up a newspaper or a popular =
website. So a month later, Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/507ad794-fd1=
d-47b2-a054-4435c57f4775?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and I started writing the Weekly Dose of Optimism [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/3787b252-d76f-4029-81c2-98d505f9da63?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to share the stori=
es of the people doing insanely hard things for the benefit of humanity.=20
Two years later, the world, or at least our little corner of it, feels a wh=
ole lot more optimistic. When people pull off incredible things, the roar o=
f the cheers drowns out the snark and the boos. There=E2=80=99s a sense tha=
t every problem is solvable, even, and especially, if it=E2=80=99s going to=
 take a lot of work to solve it.   =20
That spirit was on full display at Reindustrialize. Every speaker and panel=
ist talked about the magnitude of the challenge ahead, and each one seemed =
to relish the struggle. As Dean Ball wrote in his reflections on the event =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/62ac5b4e-5454-4f8c-9370-396aa77f9415?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:=20
In the last year, I=E2=80=99ve sensed a vibe shift=E2=80=A6 I associate thi=
s vibe shift with an earnest desire to build=E2=80=94new factories, new ene=
rgy sources, new institutions. A recognition that creating new things is pr=
eferable to arguing over how to redistribute the things we already have. A =
recognition that history is not over.
I=E2=80=99ve had trouble finding the right word to describe this shift. The=
n, at the Reindustrialize [ https://substack.com/redirect/7b809a8b-e02b-4be=
9-bbc7-2f15fe0e0e18?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ] conference this week in Detroit, Hadrian [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/fdb50164-4923-4fdc-8e91-952500b37c42?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] CEO Chris Power found the words =
for me: Seriousness, he said. America, Power argues, is becoming serious ag=
